T\").\n\nDespite the caveats in the reporting, the evidence shows that:\n- The SDNY court specifically referenced an \"allegued suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein\"\n- The AP/PBS report described it as a note \"purported to be written by Jeffrey Epstein\" \n- This constitutes \"credible reporting\" as defined in the market terms, even though it carries caveats\n\nOn balance, given the preponderance of evidence standard and the specific language of the market rule which accounts for \"credibly reported\" rather than definitively proven authorship, the evidence supports that the note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide/communication note made publicly available before the deadline.\n\n","contentIndex":0,"partial":{"api":"openai-completions","content":[{"text":"","type":"text"},{"arguments":{"args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows by a preponderance of evidence that a note was officially unsealed by a federal court and credibly reported by AP/PBS as purportedly written by Epstein and intended as a suicide/final message, made publicly available before May 8, 2026 deadline. Though caveats exist, the market rule explicitly accounts for 'credibly reported' authorship rather than definitive proof.\"}","tool":"aar_submit_council_vote"},"id":"call_7f1cd56a73b649369de7bda9","name":"mcp","type":"toolCall"}],"model":"qwen/qwen3-coder-plus","provider":"openrouter","responseId":"gen-1782800378-CMkkEgAuydOGaNUMlkjp","role":"assistant","stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782800378119,"usage":{"cacheRead":31552,"cacheWrite":0,"cost":{"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"input":0,"output":0,"total":0},"input":2143,"output":682,"totalTokens":34377}},"type":"text_end"},"message":{"api":"openai-completions","content":[{"text":"","type":"text"},{"arguments":{"args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows by a preponderance of evidence that a note was officially unsealed by a federal court and credibly reported by AP/PBS as purportedly written by Epstein and intended as a suicide/final message, made publicly available before May 8, 2026 deadline. Though caveats exist, the market rule explicitly accounts for 'credibly reported' authorship rather than definitive proof.\"}","tool":"aar_submit_council_vote"},"id":"call_7f1cd56a73b649369de7bda9","name":"mcp","type":"toolCall"}],"model":"qwen/qwen3-coder-plus","provider":"openrouter","responseId":"gen-1782800378-CMkkEgAuydOGaNUMlkjp","role":"assistant","stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782800378119,"usage":{"cacheRead":31552,"cacheWrite":0,"cost":{"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"input":0,"output":0,"total":0},"input":2143,"output":682,"totalTokens":34377}},"type":"message_update"}
{"type":"message_update","assistantMessageEvent":{"type":"toolcall_end","contentIndex":1,"toolCall":{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_7f1cd56a73b649369de7bda9","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows by a preponderance of evidence that a note was officially unsealed by a federal court and credibly reported by AP/PBS as purportedly written by Epstein and intended as a suicide/final message, made publicly available before May 8, 2026 deadline. Though caveats exist, the market rule explicitly accounts for 'credibly reported' authorship rather than definitive proof.\"}"}},"partial":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now that I have reviewed the case details and evidence, I'll analyze the key points to make my decision.\n\nBased on my review of the arbitration record:\n\n1. The proposition is: \"By May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, a message or note credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication had been made publicly available.\"\n\n2. Key admitted evidence includes:\n   - PX-1 (case packet): Defines the market rule requiring \"a message or note written by Jeffrey Epstein, intended as a suicide note, [to] be made publicly available by the listed date\"\n   - PX-2 (SDNY order): Shows a May 6, 2026 court order granting unsealing of \"an alleged suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein\" \n   - PX-3 (AP/PBS report): Reports the note was made public on May 6, 2026, describing it as \"a note purported to be written by Jeffrey Epstein\"\n   - D-1 (Business Insider): Reports Mark Epstein claiming the note is a forgery, but also contains counterweights\n\n3. All sides acknowledge that public availability occurred before the May 8 deadline: the SDNY court order dates to May 6, 2026, and the AP/PBS report was published May 6, 2026 (updated May 7).\n\n4. The core dispute concerns the \"credible reporting\" requirement for authorship. While PX-2 and PX-3 both use caveat language (\"alleged,\" \"purported,\" \"claimed\"), the plaintiff argues this satisfies the \"credibly reported\" standard under a preponderance standard, since it comes from official court sources and major news outlets.\n\n5. Both sides agree that the note contains content consistent with a suicide/final message (\"choosing the time to say goodbye,\" \"NO FUN,\" \"NOT WORTH IT\").\n\nDespite the caveats in the reporting, the evidence shows that:\n- The SDNY court specifically referenced an \"allegued suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein\"\n- The AP/PBS report described it as a note \"purported to be written by Jeffrey Epstein\" \n- This constitutes \"credible reporting\" as defined in the market terms, even though it carries caveats\n\nOn balance, given the preponderance of evidence standard and the specific language of the market rule which accounts for \"credibly reported\" rather than definitively proven authorship, the evidence supports that the note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide/communication note made publicly available before the deadline.\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_7f1cd56a73b649369de7bda9","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows by a preponderance of evidence that a note was officially unsealed by a federal court and credibly reported by AP/PBS as purportedly written by Epstein and intended as a suicide/final message, made publicly available before May 8, 2026 deadline. Though caveats exist, the market rule explicitly accounts for 'credibly reported' authorship rather than definitive proof.\"}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-coder-plus","usage":{"input":2143,"output":682,"cacheRead":31552,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":34377,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782800378119,"responseId":"gen-1782800378-CMkkEgAuydOGaNUMlkjp"}},"message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now that I have reviewed the case details and evidence, I'll analyze the key points to make my decision.\n\nBased on my review of the arbitration record:\n\n1. The proposition is: \"By May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, a message or note credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication had been made publicly available.\"\n\n2. Key admitted evidence includes:\n   - PX-1 (case packet): Defines the market rule requiring \"a message or note written by Jeffrey Epstein, intended as a suicide note, [to] be made publicly available by the listed date\"\n   - PX-2 (SDNY order): Shows a May 6, 2026 court order granting unsealing of \"an alleged suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein\" \n   - PX-3 (AP/PBS report): Reports the note was made public on May 6, 2026, describing it as \"a note purported to be written by Jeffrey Epstein\"\n   - D-1 (Business Insider): Reports Mark Epstein claiming the note is a forgery, but also contains counterweights\n\n3. All sides acknowledge that public availability occurred before the May 8 deadline: the SDNY court order dates to May 6, 2026, and the AP/PBS report was published May 6, 2026 (updated May 7).\n\n4. The core dispute concerns the \"credible reporting\" requirement for authorship. While PX-2 and PX-3 both use caveat language (\"alleged,\" \"purported,\" \"claimed\"), the plaintiff argues this satisfies the \"credibly reported\" standard under a preponderance standard, since it comes from official court sources and major news outlets.\n\n5. Both sides agree that the note contains content consistent with a suicide/final message (\"choosing the time to say goodbye,\" \"NO FUN,\" \"NOT WORTH IT\").\n\nDespite the caveats in the reporting, the evidence shows that:\n- The SDNY court specifically referenced an \"allegued suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein\"\n- The AP/PBS report described it as a note \"purported to be written by Jeffrey Epstein\" \n- This constitutes \"credible reporting\" as defined in the market terms, even though it carries caveats\n\nOn balance, given the preponderance of evidence standard and the specific language of the market rule which accounts for \"credibly reported\" rather than definitively proven authorship, the evidence supports that the note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide/communication note made publicly available before the deadline.\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_7f1cd56a73b649369de7bda9","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows by a preponderance of evidence that a note was officially unsealed by a federal court and credibly reported by AP/PBS as purportedly written by Epstein and intended as a suicide/final message, made publicly available before May 8, 2026 deadline. Though caveats exist, the market rule explicitly accounts for 'credibly reported' authorship rather than definitive proof.\"}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-coder-plus","usage":{"input":2143,"output":682,"cacheRead":31552,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":34377,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782800378119,"responseId":"gen-1782800378-CMkkEgAuydOGaNUMlkjp"}}
{"type":"message_end","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now that I have reviewed the case details and evidence, I'll analyze the key points to make my decision.\n\nBased on my review of the arbitration record:\n\n1. The proposition is: \"By May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, a message or note credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication had been made publicly available.\"\n\n2. Key admitted evidence includes:\n   - PX-1 (case packet): Defines the market rule requiring \"a message or note written by Jeffrey Epstein, intended as a suicide note, [to] be made publicly available by the listed date\"\n   - PX-2 (SDNY order): Shows a May 6, 2026 court order granting unsealing of \"an alleged suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein\" \n   - PX-3 (AP/PBS report): Reports the note was made public on May 6, 2026, describing it as \"a note purported to be written by Jeffrey Epstein\"\n   - D-1 (Business Insider): Reports Mark Epstein claiming the note is a forgery, but also contains counterweights\n\n3. All sides acknowledge that public availability occurred before the May 8 deadline: the SDNY court order dates to May 6, 2026, and the AP/PBS report was published May 6, 2026 (updated May 7).\n\n4. The core dispute concerns the \"credible reporting\" requirement for authorship. While PX-2 and PX-3 both use caveat language (\"alleged,\" \"purported,\" \"claimed\"), the plaintiff argues this satisfies the \"credibly reported\" standard under a preponderance standard, since it comes from official court sources and major news outlets.\n\n5. Both sides agree that the note contains content consistent with a suicide/final message (\"choosing the time to say goodbye,\" \"NO FUN,\" \"NOT WORTH IT\").\n\nDespite the caveats in the reporting, the evidence shows that:\n- The SDNY court specifically referenced an \"allegued suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein\"\n- The AP/PBS report described it as a note \"purported to be written by Jeffrey Epstein\" \n- This constitutes \"credible reporting\" as defined in the market terms, even though it carries caveats\n\nOn balance, given the preponderance of evidence standard and the specific language of the market rule which accounts for \"credibly reported\" rather than definitively proven authorship, the evidence supports that the note was credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide/communication note made publicly available before the deadline.\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_7f1cd56a73b649369de7bda9","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows by a preponderance of evidence that a note was officially unsealed by a federal court and credibly reported by AP/PBS as purportedly written by Epstein and intended as a suicide/final message, made publicly available before May 8, 2026 deadline. Though caveats exist, the market rule explicitly accounts for 'credibly reported' authorship rather than definitive proof.\"}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-coder-plus","usage":{"input":2143,"output":682,"cacheRead":31552,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":34377,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782800378119,"responseId":"gen-1782800378-CMkkEgAuydOGaNUMlkjp"}}
